      <h3 class="eni-section-title">Policy context and targets</h3>
      <h4>Policy context description</h4>
      <p>The National Strategy on Biological Diversity and its Action Plan for 2015-2020 (NBSAP), 2015, provides policy framework for further capacity building and measures for conservation of biodiversity and improvement management and extension of protected areas in Moldova.
      https://www.cbd.int/doc/world/md/md-nbsap-v2-en.pdf</p>

      <p>The state-funded nature policy is promoted by the Law Nr. 1538 of 25.02.1998 on State-protected areas found.  This Law establishes the legal bases of the creation and functioning of the state-funded nature reserve, its principles, mechanism and mode of preservation, as well as the attributions of central and local public authorities, non-governmental organizations and citizens in this field.
      http://lex.justice.md/index.php?action=view&view=doc&lang=1&id=311614</p>

      <p>Government Decision Nr. 803 of 19.06.2002  approves the Regulation on Procedure for establishing the natural protected area regime
      http://lex.justice.md/index.php?action=view&view=doc&lang=1&id=304836</p>

      <p>The United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) aimed at the establishment and maintenance of comprehensive, effectively managed and ecologically representative national and regional systems of protected areas. Under CBD, the Strategic Plan for Biodiversity 2011-2020 was adopted which requires that by 2020, at least 17 per cent of terrestrial and inland water areas, and 10 per cent of coastal and marine areas, especially areas of particular importance for biodiversity and ecosystem services, are conserved through effectively and equitably managed, ecologically representative and well-connected systems of protected areas and other effective area-based conservation measures, and integrated into the wider landscapes and seascapes (Target 11).</p>

      <h4>Targets</h4>
      <p>National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan 2015-2020 of the Republic of Moldova set 10% of the country’s territory to be under protection by 2020.</p>

      <p>The Aichi target 11 of the Convention on Biological Diversity is set, by 2020, at least 17 per cent of terrestrial and inland water, and 10 per cent of coastal and marine areas, especially areas of particular importance for biodiversity and ecosystem services, are conserved through effectively and equitably managed, ecologically representative and well connected systems of protected areas and other effective area-based conservation measures, and integrated into the wider landscapes and seascapes.</p>

